{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ἄλλως</b>, <br /> <i>Doric dialect</i> ἀλλῶς, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Apollonius Dyscolus Grammaticus “de Adverbiis;” 175.13, \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<i>adverb</i> of ἄλλος, <b>otherwise,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 19.401, etc.: frequently with other _adverbs_, ἄ. πως\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] <b>in</b> some <b>other way,</b> ἄ. οὐδαμῶς <b>in</b> no <b>other wise,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 343b, 526a, etc.; πως ἄ. 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 2.6.39; ἄ. καὶ ἄ. 5th c.AD: Hierocles Platonicus Philosophus “in Carmen Aureum - FPG” 23p.468M. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> καὶ ἄλλως and <b>besides</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"compare (ἄλλος 11.8), ἀγήνωρ ἐστὶ καὶ ἄλλως 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 9.699\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; a woman is described as very tall καὶ ἄ. εὐειδής[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.60, etc.; ἀρίστου καὶ ἄ. φρονιμωτάτου 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 118:—so ἄ. δέ.. 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 6.105, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Aves” 1476; ἄλλως τε 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 1114, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 8.142. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__2.b</b></Level4> <b>at all events, any how,</b> εἴ πέρ γε καὶ ἄ. ἐθέλει.. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.16\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>].; ἄλλως alone, εἰ ἄ. βούλοιτο[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 8.30; ἐπείπερ ἄλλως.. εἰς Ἄργος κίεις 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 680. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> frequently in phrase ἄλλως τε καί.. <b>both otherwise and</b>.., i.e. <b>especially, above all,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Eumenides” 473, 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 1.70, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; strengthened, ἄ. τε πάντως καί.. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 636, “Eu.” 726\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; frequently followed by ἤν, εἰ, ἐπειδή, <b>especially</b> if.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “περὶ τῶν ἐν κεφαλη—ͅ τρωμάτων” 21, 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 1.81, 2.3\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; by <i>participle</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 4.104, 7.80:—without καί, ἄ. τε ἐάν 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 1.2.59; ἄλλως τε ἐπειδή 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 2.51, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Meno” 85e, etc. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>otherwise than</b> something implied, <b>differently,</b> τοῦτ᾽ οὐκ ἔστιν ἄ. εἶπαι to deny it, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 6.124\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; οὐκ ἄ. λέγω I say no <b>otherwise,</b> i.e. I say <b>so,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hecuba” 302: hence, \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> <b>far otherwise,</b> i.e. <b>better,</b> οὐδέ κεν ἄλλως οὐδὲ θεὸς τεύξειε[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 8.176, compare 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 14.53. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.3</b></Level3> more frequently, <b>otherwise than should be, at random, without aim or purpose,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 14.124, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 3.16, 4.77, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]:—<b>in uain,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 23.144; frequently in Trag. and Comedy texts, ἀλλ᾽ ἄ. πονεῖ 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 1151, compare 333, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Medea” 1030, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 11\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; with <i>substantive</i>, εἴδωλον ἄ. <b>mere</b> image, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 947; ἀριθμὸν ἄ. 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Troades” 476; παρὰ καιρὸν ἄ. [prev. author] “IA” 800; ἀριθμός, πρόβατ᾽ ἄ. 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Nubes” 1203; ὄχλος ἄ. καὶ βασκανία 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 19.24, compare 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 8.78\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τὴν ἄ., i.e. ἄγουσαν ὁδόν, <b>in vain,</b> λέγειν[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 3.21; ψηφίζεσθαι 19.181, compare 4th-3rd c.BC: Philemo Comicus 51, etc.\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; also, <b>in no particular way,</b> i.e. <b>concerning indiffcrent matters,</b> οἱ ἀγῶνες οὐδέποτε τὴν ἄ., ἄλλ᾽ ἀεὶ τὴν περὶ αὑτοῦ[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Theaetetus” 172e; τὴν ἄ. θεωρεῖν 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 650a\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τήν γε ἄλλως <b>otherwise,</b> i.e. <b>generally,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd-3rd c.AD: Dio Cassius Historicus 38.24, 42.50\">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]:—<b>for nothing,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 3.139\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: —<b>otherwise than right, wrongly,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator “Epistulae” 1.12, etc.\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G0247","accentedUnicode":"ἄλλως","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G0243","matchingForm":"ἄλλος","stepTransliteration":"allos","gloss":"another","_zh_tw_Gloss":"別的","_es_Gloss":"otro","_zh_Gloss":"别的"}],"shortDef":"differently","mediumDef":"<b>otherwise, differently</b> <ref='1Ti.5.25'>1Tim. 5:25</ref>*","stepGloss":"otherwise","stepTransliteration":"allōs","count":1,"_es_Definition":"de otro modo ; las obras que son diferentes (1TI.5:25)","_zh_tw_Definition":"否則, 不然 (提前 5:25)","_zh_Definition":"否则, 不然 